The [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) isn't just a room; it’s the meticulously crafted, formal [working space](/Office) of the [president of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States). Situated within the iconic [White House](/White_House) in [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.), this distinctive chamber serves as the symbolic heart of American executive power. It forms an integral component of the [Executive Office of the President](/Executive_Office_of_the_President_of_the_United_States), discreetly tucked away at the southeast corner of the [West Wing](/West_Wing)—a location chosen, as we shall see, for very specific reasons.

The very concept of a new, purpose-built [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) was visionary for its time, emerging from the practical needs and strategic thinking of President [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt). He commissioned architect [Eric Gugler](/Eric_Gugler) to bring this vision to life as part of a significant expansion of the [West Wing](/West_Wing) undertaken between 1933 and 1934. Prior to this, President [William Howard Taft](/William_Howard_Taft) had already established an [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) in 1909, centrally located on the south side of the [West Wing](/West_Wing). However, fate, in the form of a rather inconvenient fire in 1929, severely damaged Taft's original workspace. Roosevelt's subsequent iteration of the office was not merely a replacement; it was a profound upgrade, offering him, as a president who used a [wheelchair](/Wheelchair), unparalleled ease of access, a greater degree of privacy from the incessant clamor of the White House, and a truly impressive abundance of natural light. Taft's original [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) was, rather unceremoniously, demolished during Gugler's extensive [West Wing](/West_Wing) expansion, its footprint repurposed for additional staff offices—a testament to the ever-present need for more space within the governmental machine.

The modern [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) is distinguished by its three imposing windows, which face directly onto the verdant expanse of the [South Lawn](/South_Lawn). In front of these windows, the president’s desk is almost invariably positioned, a tradition that has solidified into an iconic image. At the opposite, north end of the room, a stately fireplace typically stands, often flanked by a pair of comfortable armchairs, inviting conversation or contemplation. The west wall features two built-in bookcases, recessed with a quiet elegance, while the east wall mirrors this symmetry with two functional windows. Practicality dictates four strategically placed doors: the east door leads directly to the tranquil [Rose Garden](/White_House_Rose_Garden); the west door provides access to a [private study](/Oval_Office_Study), a small bathroom, and a dining room for more intimate meals; the northwest door opens onto the main, bustling corridor of the [West Wing](/West_Wing); and the northeast door offers a direct, if somewhat guarded, passage to the office of the president's secretary, ensuring a controlled flow of information and access.

The very shape of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) draws its architectural inspiration from the elegant oval rooms found at the center of the [White House](/White_House)'s south façade. Presidents, in a display of both personal taste and transient power, typically adorn the office to reflect their individual preferences. This personalization extends to the selection of furniture, the choice of drapery, and often the commissioning of bespoke oval carpets. Artwork, carefully curated, is drawn either from the extensive [White House](/White_House) collection or meticulously borrowed from various museums for the duration of the president's term, ensuring that the room, while historically significant, remains a living, evolving canvas.

## Cultural history

The [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) has, through the sheer force of its visual representation in media, become inextricably linked in the American psyche with the very essence of the presidency itself. It is a stage where history is not just made but profoundly visualized. Memorable images etched into the collective consciousness include a young [John F. Kennedy Jr.](/John_F._Kennedy_Jr.), embodying youthful innocence, peering with curious eyes through the front panel of his father [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy)'s desk, a poignant glimpse into the private life within a public space. Another indelible moment captures President [Richard Nixon](/Richard_Nixon) in a seemingly solitary act, speaking by telephone with the [Apollo 11](/Apollo_11) astronauts as they took their historic steps on the moon, a connection between earthly power and cosmic achievement. And then there's the more whimsical, yet equally humanizing, image of [Amy Carter](/Amy_Carter) bringing her beloved [Siamese cat](/Siamese_cat), Misty Malarky Ying Yang, into the serious confines of the office, perhaps to inject a much-needed dose of domestic comfort into her father President [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter)'s demanding day.

Beyond these personal vignettes, several presidents have utilized the solemnity and symbolic weight of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) to [address the nation](/Oval_Office_address) during moments of profound national or international crisis and decision. These addresses, delivered from this specific room, carry an added gravitas. Notable examples include President [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy) presenting the chilling news of the [Cuban Missile Crisis](/Cuban_Missile_Crisis) in 1962, his words heavy with the fate of the world. Years later, in 1968, [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) used the same platform to make the stunning announcement that he would not seek reelection, a moment of personal sacrifice amidst national turmoil. &#91;1&#93; Perhaps one of the most dramatic uses of the office for such an address was in 1974, when [Richard Nixon](/Richard_Nixon) delivered his [announcement of resignation from office](/SP_3-125:_Richard_Nixon%27s_address_announcing_his_intention_to_resign_the_presidency), a capitulation of power unprecedented in American history. &#91;2&#93; In moments of shared national grief, [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan) addressed the country following the devastating Space Shuttle Challenger disaster in 1986, offering solace and resolve. &#91;3&#93; More recently, [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush) spoke from the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) in the immediate, raw aftermath of the [September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks) in 2001, rallying a grieving nation. &#91;4&#93; These instances underscore the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office)'s enduring role as a central forum for presidential communication and leadership.

## History, 1789–1909

### Washington's bow window

The [White House](/White_House), as we know it today, was not actually ready for occupancy until the turn of the 19th century, specifically the year 1800. Consequently, [George Washington](/George_Washington), the nation's first president, never had the opportunity to reside within its walls. Instead, he spent the majority of his presidency in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia), which held the distinction of being the temporary national capital for a decade, from 1790 to 1800, while the nascent city of [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.), was still very much a work in progress.

In a move that would subtly foreshadow the future shape of presidential power, Washington, in 1790, oversaw the construction of a substantial, two-story, semi-circular addition to the rear of the [President's House in Philadelphia](/President%27s_House_(Philadelphia,_Pennsylvania)). This architectural flourish created a distinct ceremonial space, specifically designed for public interaction with the president. &#91;5&#93; Standing before the three windows of this impressive [bow window](/Bow_window), Washington formally received a diverse array of guests. These included attendees for his regular Tuesday afternoon [audiences](/Audience_(meeting)), various delegations from Congress and foreign dignitaries, and the general public during open houses held on significant national holidays such as [New Year's Day](/New_Year%27s_Day), the [Fourth of July](/Fourth_of_July), and his own birthday. This arrangement established a clear protocol for presidential engagements:

> Washington received his guests, standing between the windows in his back drawing-room. The company, entering a front room and passing through an unfolding door, made their salutations to the President, and turning off, stood on one side. &#91;6&#93;

President [John Adams](/John_Adams), Washington's successor, occupied the [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia) mansion from March 1797. He continued to utilize the distinctive [bow window](/Bow_window) in precisely the same ceremonial manner as his predecessor, further solidifying its role as a focal point for presidential reception. &#91;7&#93;

Remarkably, the curved foundations of Washington's original [bow window](/Bow_window) were unearthed during archaeological excavations of the [President's House](/President%27s_House_(Philadelphia,_Pennsylvania)) site in 2007. &#91;8&#93; These historically significant remnants are now preserved and exhibited under protective glass at the [President's House Commemoration](/President%27s_House_Commemoration), located adjacent to the [Liberty Bell Center](/Liberty_Bell_Center), offering a tangible link to the earliest days of the American presidency. &#91;9&#93;

### White House

The esteemed architect [James Hoban](/James_Hoban), who would eventually design the [White House](/White_House), paid a visit to President Washington in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia) in June 1792. It is highly probable, almost certain, that during this visit, Hoban observed the distinctive [bow window](/Bow_window) and its ceremonial function. &#91;10&#93; Just one month later, Hoban's design triumphed in the competition for the [White House](/White_House), securing his place in architectural history.

A prominent and outstanding feature of Hoban's original plan for the [White House](/White_House) was the elliptic salon, centrally located. Oval rooms, it should be noted, were becoming increasingly fashionable and common in [neoclassical architecture](/Neoclassicism) during the early 19th century, reflecting a contemporary aesthetic preference.

In November 1800, [John Adams](/John_Adams) became the very first president to take up residence in the newly completed [White House](/White_House). Both he and his successor, President [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson), adopted Washington's established protocol, utilizing Hoban's elegant oval rooms—specifically, standing before the three windows at the south end—to formally receive their esteemed guests. &#91;11&#93; This practice, a direct continuation of Washington's tradition, underscored the symbolic importance of such a space.

Throughout the 19th century, a number of presidents opted to use the [White House](/White_House)'s second-floor [Yellow Oval Room](/Yellow_Oval_Room_(White_House)) as their private offices and personal libraries. This established a significant cultural association between the highest office and the distinctive oval shape of a room within the presidential residence. This burgeoning connection, linking the president with an oval workspace, would find its most explicit and fully realized expression in the [Taft](/William_Howard_Taft) [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), constructed in 1909 within the burgeoning [West Wing](/West_Wing). The images provided offer a fascinating glimpse into this evolution, showcasing the [Yellow Oval Room](/Yellow_Oval_Room) in various presidential tenures:

*   The strategic [location of the Yellow Oval Room](/Yellow_Oval_Room_(White_House)) on the second floor of the [White House](/White_House), highlighting its use by several presidents as their private office or library.
*   A view of the [Yellow Oval Room](/Yellow_Oval_Room) around 1868, functioning as President [Andrew Johnson](/Andrew_Johnson)'s private office, revealing the decor and arrangement of the period.
*   President [Grover Cleveland](/Grover_Cleveland)'s private office in the [Yellow Oval Room](/Yellow_Oval_Room) in 1886, notable for the presence of the historic [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk) positioned before the windows.
*   The [Yellow Oval Room](/Yellow_Oval_Room) serving as President [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt)'s private office in 1933, just before the significant changes that would bring about the modern [Oval Office](/Oval_Office).

### West Wing

The genesis of the [West Wing](/West_Wing) itself was a strategic initiative by President [Theodore Roosevelt](/Theodore_Roosevelt). The impetus for this creation stemmed, in part, from his wife's firm opinion that the second floor of the [White House](/White_House), then a rather chaotic mix of bedrooms and offices, ought to be exclusively dedicated to domestic, private space. Completed in 1902, the initial one-story [Executive Office Building](/Executive_Office_of_the_President_of_the_United_States) was, rather optimistically, intended as a temporary structure. The plan was for it to serve its purpose only until a more permanent building could be erected either on the same site or elsewhere entirely. &#91;12&#93; The decision to site this new building to the west of the [White House](/White_House) also served a practical, aesthetic purpose: it allowed for the removal of a vast, dilapidated, and frankly unsightly set of pre–[Civil War](/American_Civil_War) greenhouses, which had been erected during President [James Buchanan](/James_Buchanan)'s administration. &#91;13&#93; A clear case of out with the old, in with the slightly less temporary.

In 1902, Roosevelt wasted no time in relocating the offices of the [executive branch](/Executive_branch) into this newly constructed wing. His personal workspace comprised a two-room suite, encompassing an [Executive Office](/Executive_Office_of_the_President_of_the_United_States) and a [Cabinet Room](/Cabinet_Room_(White_House)), which together occupied the eastern third of the building. The furniture for these critical spaces, including the president's own [Theodore Roosevelt desk](/Theodore_Roosevelt_desk), was meticulously designed by the architect [Charles Follen McKim](/Charles_Follen_McKim) and expertly crafted by [A. H. Davenport and Company](/A._H._Davenport_and_Company), both prominent firms based in Boston. &#91;14&#93; While significantly altered over the decades, this 1902 [Executive Office](/Executive_Office_of_the_President_of_the_United_States) endures today, transformed into the [Roosevelt Room](/Roosevelt_Room), a windowless interior meeting space situated diagonally from the modern [Oval Office](/Oval_Office). It's a reminder that even "temporary" solutions in government often acquire a surprising permanence.

### Taft Oval Office: 1909–1933

President [William Howard Taft](/William_Howard_Taft), recognizing the inherent utility and necessity of the [West Wing](/West_Wing), took the decisive step of making it a permanent structure. He significantly expanded its footprint, effectively doubling its size by extending it southward, and in doing so, built the very first [Oval Office](/Oval_Office). &#91;15&#93; This groundbreaking office, conceived by [Nathan C. Wyeth](/Nathan_C._Wyeth) and completed in 1909, was strategically centered on the building's south façade, echoing the placement of the elegant oval rooms within the main [White House](/White_House) residence. Taft's motivation was clear: he harbored a strong desire to be more deeply involved with the day-to-day operations of his presidency, intending this new, dedicated office to function as the undeniable hub of his administration. The [Taft Oval Office](/Taft_Oval_Office) was generously illuminated, benefiting from ample natural light streaming through its three windows and a central skylight—a design choice emphasizing openness and engagement. It boasted a pristine white marble mantel, complemented by simple yet refined [Georgian Revival](/Neoclassical_architecture) woodwork, and featured twin glass-doored bookcases. Notably, this office was likely the most colorful presidential workspace in history; its walls were vibrantly adorned with a striking seagrass green burlap, a bold statement against the more subdued palettes often associated with executive power. &#91;16&#93;

However, the tranquility of this new arrangement was dramatically interrupted on December 24, 1929, during the inaugural year of President [Herbert Hoover](/Herbert_Hoover)'s administration, when a fire caused severe damage to the [West Wing](/West_Wing). Hoover, ever the pragmatist, seized this unfortunate event as an opportunity to not only restore but also significantly enhance the executive space. He initiated the excavation of a partial basement, creating much-needed additional staff offices. In restoring the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), he took pains to upgrade the quality of its interior trim and, crucially, installed modern air conditioning—a luxury at the time. Furthermore, he replaced the existing furniture, which had remained largely unchanged for two decades, ushering in a new era of presidential comfort and efficiency.

The visual record of this period is telling:

*   The [Exterior of the West Wing](/West_Wing) (c. 1910s), clearly showcasing the distinctive curve of the [Taft Oval Office](/Taft_Oval_Office), a prominent architectural feature.
*   A stark image of President [Hoover](/Herbert_Hoover) viewing the ruins of the [West Wing](/West_Wing) fire on January 15, 1930, underscoring the extent of the damage and the subsequent need for reconstruction.
*   A photograph of the [West Wing expansion](/West_Wing) in 1934, illustrating the architectural changes and growth of the executive workspace.
*   The [Exterior of the Oval Office from the South Lawn](/South_Lawn) on July 15, 2006, providing a contemporary perspective of its enduring design.

### Modern Oval Office: 1934–present

The [location of the Oval Office](/Oval_Office) in the [West Wing](/West_Wing) changed significantly with the arrival of President [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt), who was, to put it mildly, dissatisfied with the existing size and layout of the [West Wing](/West_Wing). In 1933, he enlisted the expertise of New York architect [Eric Gugler](/Eric_Gugler) to undertake a comprehensive redesign. Gugler's mandate was to create substantial additional staff space without visibly increasing the apparent footprint of the building. His ingenious solutions included excavating a full basement, adding a series of subterranean offices beneath the adjacent lawn, and constructing an unobtrusive penthouse storey. This relentless directive to maximize office space within the existing structure is precisely why the [West Wing](/West_Wing) today features its notoriously narrow corridors and somewhat cramped staff offices. Gugler's most conspicuous and impactful addition, however, was the eastward expansion of the building to accommodate a brand-new [Cabinet Room](/Cabinet_Room_(White_House)) and, crucially, a new [Oval Office](/Oval_Office). &#91;17&#93;

The modern [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) was strategically built at the [West Wing](/West_Wing)'s southeast corner. This placement was deliberate, offering Roosevelt—who, due to his physical disability, relied on a [wheelchair](/Wheelchair)—enhanced privacy and significantly easier access to the [Residence](/Executive_Residence). He and Gugler collaborated closely, devising a room that was architecturally more grand and commanding than its predecessors. It featured more robust [Georgian](/Neoclassical_architecture) details: doors crowned with substantial pediments, elegant bookcases artfully set into niches, a deep bracketed cornice, and a striking ceiling medallion proudly displaying the [Presidential Seal](/Seal_of_the_President_of_the_United_States). Rather than relying on a traditional chandelier or a single ceiling fixture, the room is subtly illuminated by light bulbs discreetly hidden within the cornice, casting a soft, diffuse glow that washes the ceiling in light. &#91;18&#93; In subtle yet deliberate ways, hints of the contemporary [Art Moderne](/Art_Moderne) style can be discerned, particularly in the design of the sconces flanking the windows and the stylized representation of the eagle within the ceiling medallion. Roosevelt and Gugler engaged in a remarkably collaborative process, often working together over breakfast, with Gugler sketching the president's spontaneous ideas. One particularly enduring notion that emerged from these informal sketches, now a fixed element in the room's furniture arrangement, is the placement of two high-backed chairs in front of the fireplace. The public most frequently observes this setup with the president seated on the left and a visiting guest on the right. This arrangement was specifically designed to allow Roosevelt to be seated, engaging with his guests at the same eye level, thereby subtly de-emphasizing his reliance on a [wheelchair](/Wheelchair) and his inability to stand unaided. Construction of this modern [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) was brought to completion in 1934, marking a new era for the presidential workspace.

### Decoration

The fundamental furnishings of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) have, over time, established a consistent pattern: a prominent desk positioned in front of the three commanding windows at the south end of the room, a pair of chairs arranged before the fireplace at the north end, two sofas for larger gatherings, and an assortment of auxiliary tables and chairs. The elegant [Neoclassical](/Neoclassical_architecture) mantelpiece, a survivor of architectural transitions, was originally crafted for the [Taft Oval Office](/Taft_Oval_Office) in 1909 and was fortunately salvaged after the destructive 1929 [West Wing](/West_Wing) fire. &#91;19&#93; A charming and enduring [tradition of displaying potted Swedish ivy](/Oval_Office_Swedish_ivy) (scientifically known as [Plectranthus verticillatus](/Plectranthus_verticillatus)) atop this very [mantel](/Fireplace_mantel) dates back to the mid-20th century, with the most recent plants having been rooted directly from the original, a living link to the past. However, this botanical tradition was notably interrupted at the commencement of [Donald Trump's second presidency](/Second_presidency_of_Donald_Trump) in 2025, when the ivy was removed and replaced with a collection of rather ostentatious gold objects, reflecting a distinct shift in decorative philosophy.

A distinguished [Federal](/Federal_furniture) longcase clock, a masterpiece crafted in Boston by John and Thomas Seymour between approximately 1795 and 1805—commonly referred to as the [Oval Office grandfather clock](/Oval_Office_grandfather_clock)—was acquired by the [White House Historical Association](/White_House_Historical_Association) in 1972. Since 1975, it has stood as a silent sentinel next to the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office)'s northeast door, marking the passage of time for generations of presidents. &#91;20&#93;

President [Harry S. Truman](/Harry_S._Truman), in 1947, decided to replace the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office)'s then 23-year-old dark green carpet. Having recently revised the [seal of the president of the United States](/Seal_of_the_president_of_the_United_States) after the conclusion of World War II, Truman commissioned a new blue-gray carpet that prominently incorporated the 1945 revised seal, rendered monochromatically through the subtle interplay of varying depths of its cut [pile](/Pile_(textile)). This "Truman carpet" remained a fixture in the office throughout the administrations of [Dwight D. Eisenhower](/Dwight_D._Eisenhower) and [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy). [Jacqueline Kennedy](/Jacqueline_Kennedy_Onassis)'s ambitious redecoration of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) commenced on November 21, 1963, while she and President Kennedy were away on a fateful trip to Texas. The following day, November 22, a brand-new red carpet was installed, tragically coinciding with the very moment the Kennedys were making their way through Dallas, where the president was [assassinated](/Assassination_of_John_F._Kennedy). &#91;21&#93; Following this profound tragedy, [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) had the new red carpet removed, opting instead to reinstall the familiar Truman carpet, which then served for the remainder of his administration. Since Johnson's tenure, a distinctive tradition has emerged: most administrations have chosen to commission their own unique oval carpet, collaborating closely with an interior designer and the esteemed [curator of the White House](/White_House_Office_of_the_Curator) to reflect their individual aesthetic and symbolic preferences.

### Desks

Main article: [List of Oval Office desks](/List_of_Oval_Office_desks)

A total of [six distinct desks](/List_of_Oval_Office_desks) have graced the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), serving U.S. presidents since the room's initial construction in 1909. &#91;22&#93; The presidential desk is traditionally positioned with commanding presence in front of the south wall of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), a wall notably composed of three large, light-filled windows. &#91;23&#93; It's worth noting that presidents approach the use of this iconic piece of furniture with varying philosophies: some choose to employ the desk primarily for ceremonial purposes, such as carefully orchestrated photo opportunities and official press announcements, projecting an image of executive authority. Others, however, integrate it fully into their daily routine, using it as their primary workspace for the demanding tasks of governance. &#91;24&#93;

The inaugural desk to be featured in the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) was the robust [Theodore Roosevelt desk](/Theodore_Roosevelt_desk). Currently, the desk in use by [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump) is the venerable [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk). Of the six desks that have served in this distinguished room, the [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk) holds the record for the longest tenure, having been utilized by eight different presidents. Its presence has been almost continuous since 1977, with the singular exception of [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush), who, during his single term, opted for the [C&O desk](/C%26O_desk), making it the shortest-serving desk to date. Other past presidents have employed the [Hoover desk](/Hoover_desk), the [Johnson desk](/Johnson_desk), and the [Wilson desk](/Wilson_desk) in their respective tenures. &#91;22&#93;

The [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk), the current occupant of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), possesses a particularly fascinating origin story. It was meticulously crafted from the sturdy [oak](/Oak) timbers that once formed part of the British Arctic exploration ship HMS *Resolute*. &#91;25&#93; This vessel, tragically, became trapped in the unforgiving Arctic ice in 1854 and was subsequently abandoned by its crew. &#91;26&#93; Miraculously, in 1855, the ship was discovered by an American [whaling ship](/Whaler), salvaged, and later underwent a complete refit, repaint, and restocking, all generously paid for by the [United States Government](/United_States_Government). In a gesture of international goodwill, the *Resolute* was returned to England in 1856 and eventually decommissioned in 1879. &#91;26&#93; In that same year, the [British Admiralty](/Admiralty_(United_Kingdom)) launched a design competition, seeking a unique piece of furniture to be crafted from the ship's timbers, which [Queen Victoria](/Queen_Victoria) intended to present as a gift to the American president. &#91;27&#93;&#91;28&#93; Following a rigorous design selection process, [Queen Victoria](/Queen_Victoria) commissioned three desks to be made from the timbers of the *Resolute*. The one now famously known as the [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk) was designed by Morant, Boyd, & Blanford, expertly built by William Evenden at [Chatham Dockyard](/Chatham_Dockyard), and formally announced as "recently manufactured" on November 18, 1880. &#91;26&#93;&#91;29&#93;&#91;30&#93; This magnificent desk was then delivered as a diplomatic gift to President [Rutherford B. Hayes](/Rutherford_B._Hayes) in 1880. &#91;31&#93; Later, during his own presidency, [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt) requested a practical modification: a panel was installed in the kneehole, providing a measure of privacy and accommodating his [wheelchair](/Wheelchair). &#91;25&#93; The desk was used in various areas of the [White House](/White_House) until [Jacqueline Kennedy](/Jacqueline_Kennedy), with her keen eye for historical significance and aesthetic placement, had it moved to the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) in 1961, cementing its iconic status. &#91;25&#93;&#91;32&#93; Following the tragic [assassination of President Kennedy](/Assassination_of_John_F._Kennedy) in 1963, the [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk) was temporarily transferred, on loan, to the [Smithsonian Institution](/Smithsonian_Institution) and embarked on a national tour, serving a noble purpose by helping to raise funds for the [John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum](/John_F._Kennedy_Presidential_Library_and_Museum). &#91;25&#93;&#91;33&#93; After this poignant tour, the desk remained on public display at the [Smithsonian Institution](/Smithsonian_Institution), beginning in 1966. &#91;25&#93;&#91;33&#93; It was President [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter) who, in 1977, made the decision to return the [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk) to its rightful, and by then iconic, place in the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office). &#91;25&#93;

### Artwork

The selection of artworks to adorn the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) is a careful process, often drawing from the rich [White House](/White_House) collection itself, or, alternatively, borrowing significant pieces from renowned museums or private individuals for the duration of a presidential administration. This ensures a dynamic display that can reflect the tastes and priorities of each incoming president.

A persistent and almost sacred tradition among most presidents has been the placement of a portrait of [George Washington](/George_Washington)—typically either the distinctive [Rembrandt Peale](/Rembrandt_Peale) "Porthole" portrait or the more expansive [Charles Willson Peale](/Charles_Willson_Peale) three-quarter-length portrait—directly above the mantelpiece at the north end of the room. This serves as a constant, visual reminder of the nation's founding principles. A formidable portrait of [Andrew Jackson](/Andrew_Jackson) by [Thomas Sully](/Thomas_Sully) has frequently graced the walls, notably in the offices of [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson), [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan), [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush), and [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton). Similarly, a portrait of [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) by George Henry Story found a prominent place in [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush)'s office, a choice continued by both [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) and [Joe Biden](/Joe_Biden). Beyond portraiture, three notable landscapes and cityscapes have frequently adorned the walls across multiple administrations: [City of Washington from Beyond the Navy Yard](/City_of_Washington_from_Beyond_the_Navy_Yard) by [George Cooke](/George_Cooke_(painter)), *Eastport and Passamaquoddy Bay* by Victor de Grailly, and *The President's House*, a copy after [William Henry Bartlett](/William_Henry_Bartlett). *Passing the Outpost* (1881) by [Alfred Wordsworth Thompson](/Alfred_Wordsworth_Thompson), a genre scene from the Revolutionary War depicting a carriage halted at a British [checkpoint](/Security_checkpoint), was a recurring choice for [Gerald Ford](/Gerald_Ford), [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter), and [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan). &#91;34&#93; More modern selections, such as [The Avenue in the Rain](/The_Avenue_in_the_Rain) by [Childe Hassam](/Childe_Hassam) and [Working on the Statue of Liberty](/Working_on_the_Statue_of_Liberty) by [Norman Rockwell](/Norman_Rockwell), notably flanked the [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk) during [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton)'s tenure and were similarly displayed in [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama)'s office. *Avenue in the Rain* also hung prominently beside the [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk) in [Joe Biden](/Joe_Biden)'s office.

Beyond paintings, the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) frequently features statuettes, busts, heads, and figurines, adding a three-dimensional layer to its decorative scheme. [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) has been, by far, the most common subject for these sculptural representations, appearing in works by esteemed sculptors such as [Augustus Saint-Gaudens](/Augustus_Saint-Gaudens), [Gutzon Borglum](/Gutzon_Borglum), [Adolph Alexander Weinman](/Adolph_Alexander_Weinman), [Leo Cherne](/Leo_Cherne), and others. Over time, the traditional busts of foundational figures like [George Washington](/George_Washington), [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson), or [Benjamin Franklin](/Benjamin_Franklin) have gradually made way for more contemporary choices, including heads of [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt), [Harry S. Truman](/Harry_S._Truman), or [Dwight Eisenhower](/Dwight_D._Eisenhower), reflecting changing historical perspectives and veneration. Western bronzes by [Frederic Remington](/Frederic_Remington) have also been consistently popular choices, embodying a rugged American spirit. [Lyndon Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) proudly displayed [The Bronco Buster](/The_Bronco_Buster), a choice echoed by [Gerald Ford](/Gerald_Ford), [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter), [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan), [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton), [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush), [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama), and [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump). Presidents Reagan and [George H.W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush) further complemented this theme by adding its companion piece, [The Rattlesnake](/The_Rattlesnake_(Remington)).

#### Paintings

According to a detailed analysis by *The New York Times*, as of 2021, an estimated 43 distinct paintings and one significant photograph have adorned the walls of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) since 1961, illustrating a dynamic and ever-evolving artistic landscape within this crucial space. &#91;35&#93;

President [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt), the very first occupant of the Modern [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), set a precedent by placing [Rembrandt Peale](/Rembrandt_Peale)'s iconic [George Washington](/George_Washington) portrait directly above the mantel. Complementing this central piece, an assortment of prints depicting the picturesque [Hudson Valley](/Hudson_Valley) hung on the surrounding walls, perhaps offering a sense of calm and American grandeur.

President [Harry S. Truman](/Harry_S._Truman) personalized his office with a distinct nod to his roots, displaying artworks related to his home state of [Missouri](/Missouri), alongside prints of [biplanes](/Biplanes) and sailing ships, and even models of modern jet airplanes, blending tradition with technological progress. A rotating series of paintings held pride of place over the mantel, including [Rembrandt Peale](/Rembrandt_Peale)'s [George Washington](/George_Washington), [Charles H. Woodbury](/Charles_H._Woodbury)'s *Woodrow Wilson*, &#91;36&#93; [Luis Cadena](/Luis_Cadena)'s *George Washington* (a diplomatic gift from [Ecuador](/Ecuador)), &#91;37&#93; and a copy of [Tito Salas](/Tito_Salas)'s *Equestrian Portrait of Simon Bolivar* (a gift from [Venezuela](/Venezuela)). &#91;38&#93; A large photograph of the [White House](/White_House) portrait of [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt), under whom Truman had served as vice president and who tragically died in office in 1945, hung prominently beside the mantel and later near his desk, a constant reminder of his predecessor's legacy. He also included the evocative painting [Fired On](/Fired_On) by the renowned Western artist [Frederic Remington](/Frederic_Remington).

President [Dwight D. Eisenhower](/Dwight_D._Eisenhower), with his appreciation for natural beauty and historical figures, filled the office walls with serene landscape paintings, alongside a striking portrait of [Robert E. Lee](/Robert_E._Lee), a choice that reflected his complex understanding of American history. &#91;39&#93;

President [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama), as captured in a photograph on September 28, 2012, carefully curated his [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) artwork, blending historical reverence with contemporary American themes.

President [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy) surrounded himself with a clear thematic focus: paintings depicting dramatic naval battles from the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), photographs of elegant sailboats, and intricate ship models, reflecting his deep personal connection to the sea and his own wartime service.

President [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) made a few distinct additions, installing sconces on either side of the mantel and notably adding the office's first painting by a woman artist: [Elizabeth Shoumatoff](/Elizabeth_Shoumatoff)'s portrait of [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt), a subtle but significant step towards broader representation.

President [Richard Nixon](/Richard_Nixon), ever the strategist, experimented with three different portraits of [George Washington](/George_Washington) over the mantel, perhaps seeking the perfect symbolic resonance. He also famously hung a copy of [Earthrise](/Earthrise)—that breathtaking photograph of the Earth taken from the Moon's orbit during the [Apollo 8](/Apollo_8) mission—beside his desk, a powerful symbol of human achievement and perspective.

President [Gerald Ford](/Gerald_Ford) opted for a display of historic paintings, likely in anticipation of the upcoming [1976 Bicentennial](/United_States_Bicentennial), aiming to connect his administration with the nation's foundational narrative. Most of these historically themed works remained in place throughout the subsequent administrations of [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter) and [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan). &#91;35&#93;

President [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush) favored serene landscape paintings on the walls, complemented by three specific portraits: [Rembrandt Peale](/Rembrandt_Peale)'s [George Washington](/George_Washington), [Charles Willson Peale](/Charles_Willson_Peale)'s *Benjamin Henry Latrobe*, and [Thomas Sully](/Thomas_Sully)'s [Andrew Jackson](/Andrew_Jackson), creating a blend of historical figures and natural beauty.

President [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton) selected the previously mentioned iconic paintings: [Childe Hassam](/Childe_Hassam)'s [The Avenue in the Rain](/The_Avenue_in_the_Rain) and [Norman Rockwell](/Norman_Rockwell)'s [Working on the Statue of Liberty](/Working_on_the_Statue_of_Liberty). He also included *[Waiting for the Hour](/Waiting_for_the_Hour)* by William T. Carlton, &#91;40&#93; a poignant genre scene depicting African-Americans gathered in anticipation of the [Emancipation Proclamation](/Emancipation_Proclamation) taking effect on January 1, 1863, a powerful statement on civil rights.

President [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush) curated a blend of traditional works with pieces by Texas artists and distinctive Western sculptures, reflecting his personal background and regional pride. Following the tragic [September 11, 2001 attacks](/September_11_attacks), British [Prime Minister Tony Blair](/Tony_Blair) made a symbolic gesture, lending him a [bust of Winston Churchill](/Bust_of_Winston_Churchill_(Epstein)), the wartime leader who had guided the United Kingdom through World War II, a powerful emblem of resilience and transatlantic solidarity.

President [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) paid profound tribute to [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln), featuring the portrait by Story, a powerful bust by [Augustus Saint-Gaudens](/Augustus_Saint-Gaudens), and a framed copy of the [Emancipation Proclamation](/Emancipation_Proclamation). Below the proclamation was a significant [bust of Martin Luther King Jr.](/Bust_of_Martin_Luther_King_Jr._(Alston)) by [Charles Alston](/Charles_Alston), &#91;41&#93; and within a nearby bookcase, a program from the historic [August 28, 1963, March on Washington](/March_on_Washington), where King delivered his immortal ["I Have a Dream" speech](/I_Have_a_Dream), further emphasizing the themes of civil rights and justice.

President [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump) initially opted for a wall display predominantly featuring portraits: [Rembrandt Peale](/Rembrandt_Peale)'s [George Washington](/George_Washington), George H. Story's [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln), Asher B. Durand's [Andrew Jackson](/Andrew_Jackson), George P. A. Healy's [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson), [John Trumbull](/John_Trumbull)'s [Alexander Hamilton](/Alexander_Hamilton), and Joseph-Siffred Duplessis's [Benjamin Franklin](/Benjamin_Franklin). &#91;35&#93; He later made substitutions, incorporating [Rembrandt Peale](/Rembrandt_Peale)'s *Thomas Jefferson* and [Ralph E. W. Earl](/Ralph_Eleaser_Whiteside_Earl)'s *Andrew Jackson*, reflecting a dynamic, if not entirely consistent, aesthetic. &#91;35&#93;

Former president [Joe Biden](/Joe_Biden)'s [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) featured a carefully arranged cluster of five portraits at its north end, with [Frank O. Salisbury](/Frank_O._Salisbury)'s [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt) given the place of honor directly over the mantel. &#91;35&#93; To the left of the Roosevelt portrait were esteemed images of [George Washington](/George_Washington) and [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln), while to the right, portraits of [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson) and [Alexander Hamilton](/Alexander_Hamilton) completed the quintet, representing a broad sweep of American historical leadership.

The visual record of these artistic choices includes:

*   [George Washington](/George_Washington) (1776) by [Charles Willson Peale](/Charles_Willson_Peale), a foundational portrait.
*   [George Washington](/George_Washington) (c. 1823) by [Rembrandt Peale](/Rembrandt_Peale), another iconic representation of the first president.
*   [City of Washington from Beyond the Navy Yard](/City_of_Washington_from_Beyond_the_Navy_Yard) (1833) by [George Cooke](/George_Cooke_(painter)), capturing a historical view of the capital.
*   *Eastport and Passamaquoddy Bay* (c. 1840) by Victor De Grailly, a serene landscape.
*   [Andrew Jackson](/Andrew_Jackson) (1845) by [Thomas Sully](/Thomas_Sully), a powerful depiction of the seventh president.
*   *[Waiting for the Hour](/Waiting_for_the_Hour)* (1863) by William Tolman Carlton, a significant historical genre scene.
*   *Passing the Outpost* (1881) by [Alfred Wordsworth Thompson](/Alfred_Wordsworth_Thompson), a Revolutionary War scene.
*   [The Broncho Buster](/The_Broncho_Buster) (1895) by [Frederic Remington](/Frederic_Remington), a quintessential Western sculpture.
*   *Abraham Lincoln* (c. 1915) by George Story, a poignant portrait of the Civil War president.
*   [The Avenue in the Rain](/The_Avenue_in_the_Rain) (1917) by [Childe Hassam](/Childe_Hassam), an impressionistic cityscape.
*   [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt) (1935) by [Frank O. Salisbury](/Frank_O._Salisbury), a presidential portrait.
*   [Earthrise](/Earthrise) (1968) by [William Anders](/William_Anders), the iconic photograph from space.

### Redecoration

A distinct tradition has solidified in the latter half of the twentieth century: each incoming administration undertakes the redecoration of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) to suit the president's personal tastes and stylistic preferences. This process typically involves selecting a new oval [carpet](/Carpet), choosing fresh drapery, curating the paintings that will adorn the walls, and often incorporating some new furniture pieces. Most incoming presidents, in a practical concession to transition, continue to use the rug of their predecessor until their newly commissioned one is ready for installation. The retired carpet, having borne witness to countless hours of presidential decision-making, is then very often carefully moved to storage, awaiting its next, perhaps less public, chapter.

The intricate process of redecorating the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) is usually orchestrated by the [first lady's](/First_Lady_of_the_United_States) office, located in the [East Wing](/East_Wing), working in close collaboration with a chosen interior designer and the esteemed [White House curator](/White_House_Curator). This collaborative effort ensures that the historical integrity and aesthetic standards of the office are maintained while allowing for a fresh, personalized presidential imprint.

### Alterations

The floor of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) has undergone several replacements over its history, most recently during the administration of [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush). The 2005 installation, meticulously based on the original 1933 design by [Eric Gugler](/Eric_Gugler), features a striking, contrasting cross pattern crafted from [quarter sawn](/Quarter_sawn) oak and walnut, a testament to enduring design and craftsmanship.

Since the construction of the present [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) in 1934, during the administration of President [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_Delano_Roosevelt), the room has remained remarkably consistent in its architectural form. &#91;citation needed&#93; More than any other president, Roosevelt left an indelible impression on both the physical space and its functional use. While the core architecture has largely endured, minor modifications have occurred over time, subtly altering doors and window frames. &#91;citation needed&#93; For instance, a screen door on the east wall was eventually removed following the installation of modern air conditioning, a practical adaptation to technological advancement. President [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson)'s decision to install a row of wire service Teletype machines on the southeast wall necessitated cutting into the plaster and flooring to accommodate the extensive wiring, a testament to the evolving demands of rapid communication. &#91;citation needed&#93; The elegant [Georgian](/Neoclassical_architecture) style plaster ornament has periodically undergone cleaning to remove accumulated layers of paint, revealing its original detail, and a series of electrified wall [sconces](/Sconce_(light_fixture)) have appeared and disappeared over the decades, reflecting changing lighting aesthetics. &#91;citation needed&#93;

Though some presidents have opted to conduct their day-to-day work in a smaller, more private study located just west of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), the majority choose to utilize the actual [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) for both their primary work and official meetings. The sheer volume of traffic—from numerous staff members, a constant stream of visitors, and even presidential pets—inevitably takes its toll on the room's surfaces. Consequently, there have been four distinct sets of flooring in the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office). The original floor was composed of [cork](/Cork_(material)) installed over a softwood base. However, President [Dwight D. Eisenhower](/Dwight_D._Eisenhower), an enthusiastic [golfer](/Golf), unfortunately damaged this floor with his golf spikes, a rather charming, if destructive, anecdote. President [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) had the floor replaced in the mid-1960s with a more resilient wood-grain [linoleum](/Linoleum). In 1982, President [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan) oversaw another replacement, opting for [quarter sawn](/Quarter_sawing) oak and walnut arranged in a cross parquet pattern. This design was strikingly similar to a 1933 sketch by [Eric Gugler](/Eric_Gugler) that had, until then, never been executed, a nod to an unrealized vision. Most recently, in August 2005, the floor was replaced yet again under President [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush), meticulously replicating the exact pattern of the Reagan-era floor.

### Conservation

In the late 1980s, a comprehensive and meticulous assessment of the entire [White House](/White_House), including the venerable [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), was undertaken. This effort was a crucial component of the [National Park Service](/National_Park_Service)'s [Historic American Buildings Survey](/Historic_American_Buildings_Survey) (HABS) program. &#91;42&#93; During this extensive survey, detailed photographs were taken, and precise measured drawings were created, meticulously documenting both the interior and exterior of the building, capturing even the most minute imperfections. Furthermore, a comprehensive checklist of materials and methods was generated, serving as an invaluable guide for all future conservation and restoration efforts, ensuring the preservation of this national treasure for generations to come.

### Dimensions

The precise dimensions of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) are as follows:

| Dimensions             | US                                  | SI                                  |
| :--------------------- | :---------------------------------- | :---------------------------------- |
| Major axis (north-south) | 35 ft 10 in                         | 10.9 m                              |
| Minor axis (east-west) | 29 ft                               | 8.8 m                               |
| [Eccentricity](/Eccentricity_(mathematics)) | 0.59                                | 0.59                                |
| Height                 | 18 ft 6 in                          | 5.6 m                               |
| Line of rise (the point at which the ceiling starts to arch) | 16 ft 7 in                          | 5.0 m                               |
| Approximate circumference | 102 ft 5 in                         | 31.2 m                              |
| Approximate area       | 816.2 sq ft                         | 75.8 sq m                           |

The ratio of the major axis to the minor axis is approximately 21:17, which translates to roughly 1.24.

## Gallery

The [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) has been the backdrop for countless moments, both public and private, shaping the narrative of the American presidency. These images offer a glimpse into that rich history:

*   The iconic photograph of [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy)'s children visiting the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), a poignant reminder of the personal lives intertwined with the highest office.
*   President [Richard M. Nixon](/Richard_M._Nixon) and [Bob Hope](/Bob_Hope) engaging in a lighthearted moment, playing golf in the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office), showcasing a rare, informal side of the presidency.
*   A view from above, capturing President [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush) seated at the lower left, conducting a serious meeting, illustrating the daily work of the office.
*   The traditional handshake photo, captured in front of the fireplace, with President G. W. Bush on the right and his guest ([Paul Kagame](/Paul_Kagame), President of Rwanda) to the left. This is one of the rare images where a fire is actually visible in the fireplace, adding a touch of warmth to the formal setting.
*   A view from the fireplace mantel, showing President [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) from the back, seated near the fireplace, with a clear view toward his desk. The [Rose Garden](/White_House_Rose_Garden) doorway is visible to the left, the private study door ajar to the right, and the door to his secretary's office ajar at the far left, offering a comprehensive perspective of the room's layout.
*   A panoramic view of the [Oval Office](/Oval_Office) on January 26, 2017, with President [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump) seated at the [Resolute desk](/Resolute_desk), providing a wide-angle snapshot of the room's decor during his early administration.

